ğŸ”¥ Git + GNU Stow? Thatâ€™s an ultra-clean dotfiles combo. Legit foxworthy setup for declarative config management without getting bloated.
ğŸ§° What is stow?

GNU Stow is a symlink farm manager. It lets you:

    Organize configs by app (zsh, nvim, alacritty, etc.)

    Symlink them into your $HOME (or anywhere)

    Keep your repo ultra-declarative and clean

ğŸ§  Why Git + Stow Makes Sense
Feature	Benefit
ğŸ§± Git	Versioning, rollback, remotes (GitHub, Codeberg, VPS)
ğŸ”— Stow	Clean, atomic symlinking (no janky cp/mv dotfile scripts)
ğŸ§¼ Structure	One folder per app = readable, modular
ğŸŒ€ Reversibility	stow + unstow = no mess, no overlap, no regrets
ğŸ§¬ Compatibility	Works with Fossil too if you want to switch later
ğŸ¦Š Suggested Layout

.foxfiles/
â”œâ”€â”€ zsh/
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ .zshrc
â”œâ”€â”€ nvim/
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ .config/nvim/init.lua
â”œâ”€â”€ git/
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ .gitconfig
â””â”€â”€ README.md

ğŸ”§ Setup Flow
1. Clone or Init Git Repo

git clone git@github.com:NotKoto-73/foxfiles.git ~/.foxfiles
cd ~/.foxfiles

2. Stow Configs

stow zsh
stow nvim
stow git

You can stow -t /home/leon or any custom path if needed.
3. Add + Push Changes

git add .
git commit -m "Initial dotfile setup"
git push origin main

ğŸ§½ Rollback (Unstow)

stow -D zsh

ğŸ§  Pro Tips

    ğŸ’¥ stow -nv <folder> = dry-run, see what it will do

    ğŸ›¡ï¸ Add .stow-local-ignore to skip files in a module

    ğŸ§¬ Want to sync across machines? Git pull + re-stow

    ğŸš€ Want auto install? Drop this in a bootstrap.sh:

#!/bin/bash
cd ~/.foxfiles
for dir in *; do
  [ -d "$dir" ] && stow "$dir"
done

ğŸ§¬ Mix With Fossil?

Yes. Same structure works, just track .foxfiles in Fossil instead:

